  "description": "Authoritative body-hash golden vectors. body_hash / cleartext_hash in ACI receipts is sha256_hex(compact serde_json::to_vec(body)) where serde_json has the preserve_order feature on, so map key order is the INSERTION order the client sent — NOT sorted. This is the byte-for-byte target the Go encoder (Task 1.3) must reproduce; Go's encoding/json sorts map keys and will NOT match unless ordering is preserved explicitly.",
  "source": {
    "repo": "Dstack-TEE private-ai-gateway",
    "commit": "1b43f76e43c2459856faebe9cd97d8e01cb0df0c",
    "serializer": "serde_json::to_vec with crate feature preserve_order (Cargo.toml: serde_json features=[\"preserve_order\"])",
    "digest_fn": "src/aci/canonical.rs::sha256_hex == \"sha256:\"+hex(sha256(bytes))",
    "generated_by": "tests/zz_aci_vector_harness.rs::emit_body_hash_vectors (scratch harness, not committed upstream)"
  },
  "float_note": "Some bodies carry NON-INTEGER floats (temperature/top_p). serde_json parses the wire literal to f64 then re-emits via ryu shortest-round-trip (NOT verbatim: 0.70->\"0.7\", 1e0->\"1.0\"). For the realistic temperature/top_p domain (non-integer values roughly in [1e-5, 1e16)) Go's shortest-float emission matches serde byte-for-byte; whole-number floats (1.0) and exotic magnitudes (>=1e16) diverge but never occur on this wire. The strict JCS path (Canonicalize) still REJECTS all floats; only CompactJSON accepts/emits them.",
  "fields": {
    "name": "stable vector identifier",
    "note": "optional human-readable description of what the vector pins (not load-bearing)",
    "body": "the request body Value (parsed; for human readability only — order shown is insertion order)",
    "body_text": "the EXACT compact serialization as a UTF-8 string (authoritative key order)",
    "compact_hex": "lowercase hex of the compact serde_json::to_vec bytes (authoritative)",
    "sha256": "\"sha256:\"+hex(sha256(compact_hex bytes))"
  },
